He considered the difference between the two homes on each feature (e.g. a 100 sq. ft. yard versus a 400 sq. ft. yard = a 300 sq. ft. difference), and then weighed those differences together to figure out w
strategy:
I looked at two features more consistently than others -- quality of HVAC system, and quality of kitchen. 

That's because I have lived without these features, or severely compromised versions of them, and let me tell you -- you need a working kitchen! Trying to run everything off, say, a hot plate is a miserable exercise. Working with a microwave is a little better, judging by the number of microwave cookbooks, but without a stove that's operating, in good condition, it's still a miserable affair.

Same goes for A/C -- if you live in a really hot area, you'll sweat your you-know-what-off, and it'll be hard to sleep, or do anything else. It eventually escalates to the point where you spend as little time as possible at home, and you find excuses ('reasons') to avoid spending much time there, other than to put your head down (maybe).

You'll typically find these features (or lack thereof) in poorer neighborhoods. Things are better for me now, but these are examples of how going without something can make your life a lot tougher than it should be otherwise. Like the saying goes, been there, done that, bought the T-shirt.
metastrategy: As I said, I focused mainly on two features -- quality of HVAC system, and quality of kitchen -- based on going without such things in the past. I considered various other factors (e.g., size of yard, size of home, and noise pollution) somewhat lower down the scale. But those two features, quality of HVAC and kitchen, ranked ahead of all other issues, based on my personal experiences with them (as I've already detailed).

attention_check: 'I will complete this study with my full attention'
permission: Yes, I am okay with my answers to these questions
feedback: Yes, it took the amount of time specified -- given how many questions there were. I enjoyed doing this study, even if it brought me back to some things I try to avoid dwelling on (as I mentioned in my longer answers, as to how I actually made the choices). I only hope things get better in America, to where we're not having to decide all the time between a merely OK kitchen, and a very bad kitchen, for instance, because (as I said) I know what it's like not to have a working kitchen, or less than efficient working HVAC system.
